  "text": "Generally, high phosphorous removal rate would be achieved in new CWs due to the high phosphorous adsorption capacity of new substrate. As shown in Table 2 , the removal rates of TP in vertical subsurface flow CW systems were over 80%, while the values of horizontal subsurface flow systems were over 70%, which indicated that most amount of phosphorous in wastewater was retained in the CW systems, and the P retention capacity of vertical subsurface flow CW systems was a little higher than that of horizontal subsurface flow systems. Table 2 also revealed that high COD treatment efficiency was achieved in the four CW systems. It showed that vertical subsurface flow CW systems could get a higher COD removal rate than that done by horizontal subsurface flow CW systems. Moreover, higher ammonium removal rate was observed in vertical flow CW systems as well. These results were supported by relevant researches, which confirmed that BOD and ammonium removal rates were higher in vertical flow compared to those in horizontal subsurface flow [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
